article.headline: Miami wins five of last six
article.linkText: Heat end Nets' 15-game run vs. East teams
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Lamar Odom's three field goals all came in the final five minutes Sunday to help the Miami Heat beat New Jersey 104-95, ending the Nets' 15-game winning streak against Eastern Conference teams. Miami won for the fifth time in six games and remained tied with New York for seventh place in the Eastern Conference. Eddie Jones led the Heat with 23 points, including nine in the fourth quarter. Odom missed his first six shots but still finished with 15 points. Miami's Rafer Alston extended his streak of 3-pointers to 33 consecutive games, tying the franchise record set by Tim Hardaway. It's the longest streak in the league this season. Richard Jefferson scored 25 points for the Nets, who lost despite shooting 51.5 percent from the field and 90 from the line. The Heat shot 53.5 and 73 percent. The Nets, who trailed by 13 points early in the fourth quarter, reduced the deficit to 89-85 with five minutes left. But Odom sank his first basket, and following a turnover he scored again on a dunk to make it 93-85. A 3-pointer by Jones and another basket by Odom put Miami up 100-90. The clinching score came from Caron Butler, who sank a 3-pointer as the 24-second clock expired with 49 seconds left for a 103-92 lead. Butler had been 2-for-24 on 3-pointers this season. Rookie Dwyane Wade, who had come off the bench in the past two games after recovering from a bruised foot, rejoined Miami's starting lineup and scored 16 points. The Nets played without forward Kenyon Martin, a late scratch after spraining his left ankle Friday. Rodney Rogers made his fourth start of the season in place of Martin and scored 14 points. The Nets went nearly six minutes without a field goal in the second quarter and fell behind 49-37. Miami intercepted passes by Jason Kidd on consecutive possessions in the third quarter and converted both turnovers into baskets -- including a 3-pointer by Jones -- for a 74-60 lead.

Game notes
The Heat improved to 22-12 at home, second only to New Jersey in the Atlantic Division. ... Miami tied the season series 2-2. The teams play again in the final regular-season game.
